## рҹҡҖ Usage Example (`main.go`)

```go
package main

import (
	"fmt"
	"time"

	"your_module/workerpool"
)

func main() {
	// 4 workers, queue capacity of 20
	pool := workerpool.New(4, 20)

	// Submit 10 jobs
	for i := 1; i <= 10; i++ {
		id := i
		err := pool.Submit(workerpool.Job{
			ID: id,
			Handler: func() {
				time.Sleep(200 * time.Millisecond) // simulate work
				fmt.Printf("  job %d done\n", id)
			},
		})
		if err != nil {
			fmt.Printf("submit failed for job %d: %v\n", id, err)
		}
	}

	// Gracefully wait for all jobs to finish
	pool.ShutdownWithTimeout(5 * time.Second)
}
```

**Sample output:**
```
[worker 0] starting job 1
[worker 1] starting job 2
[worker 2] starting job 3
[worker 3] starting job 4
  job 1 done
[worker 0] finished job 1
...
[pool] graceful shutdown complete
```

---

## рҹ§Ә Testing Notes

| Scenario | How to test |
|---|---|
| **Race conditions** | Run with `go test -race ./...` |
| **Idempotent shutdown** | Call `Shutdown()` 5Г— concurrently вҖ” no panic, no deadlock |
| **Submit after shutdown** | Expect `ErrPoolShutdown`, never a panic |
| **Force shutdown** | Verify unstarted queued jobs are dropped; started jobs finish |
| **Queue full / backpressure** | Use `TrySubmit` and assert `false` when queue is at capacity |
| **Goroutine leak** | Use `goleak` or check `runtime.NumGoroutine()` before and after |

---

## рҹ”‘ Key Takeaways

| Principle | Implementation |
|---|---|
| No goroutine leaks | `sync.WaitGroup` joins every worker before returning |
| No send-on-closed panic | State set to `shuttingDown` *before* `close(jobChan)` inside `sync.Once` |
| In-flight jobs always complete | Workers finish their current `job.Handler()` before checking exit conditions |
| Idempotent shutdown | `sync.Once` wraps all shutdown logic |
| Backpressure | Bounded `jobChan`; `Submit` blocks; `TrySubmit` returns immediately |
